               <msContents>
                  <summary>Manuscript containing a single work. 1 copy of <title>Inshā-yi ʿAbd
                        al-Ḥayy</title>.</summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="Kings_32-item1" n="1">
                     <author key="person_k0065" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/k0065/">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">ʿAbd al-Ḥayy</persName>
                        (would that be <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="supplied"
                           key="person_k0082">Niẓām al-dīn ʿAbd al-Ḥayy Munshī</persName> ?)
                           <persName xml:lang="fa">عبد الحي</persName>
                     </author>

                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">Inshā-yi ʿAbd al-Ḥayy</title>
                     <title xml:lang="Persian">انشاى عبد الحى</title>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                     <incipit xml:lang="fa"/>
                     <explicit xml:lang="fa" defective="true"/>
                     <colophon></colophon>
                     <note>According to a note on the flyleaf ms is in hand of 'Abd al-Hayy Munshi,
                        i.e. the author, Nizam al-din 'Abd al-Hayy Astarabadi (who was an early
                        master of ta'liq; secretary to Abu Sa'id Gurkan, a great grandson of Timur;
                        he was a pupil of Ja'far Baysunghuri, who died in Tabriz in 907 - ref.:
                        fazAyilI, aTlas al-khaTT, p.325-6), who was the master of Mulla Darvish
                        (surely, Mawlana Darvish 'Abdallah Balkhi, another master of ta'liq, who was
                        secretary to the children of Abu Sa'id Gurkan, of Husayn Bayqara and his
                        children, and of Uzbek Shaybani (d.916)). However, there is no name in the
                        colophon and the date 941 would not allow for this to be an autograph. 941
                        dates the ms to 10 years into the reign of Shah Tahmasp and 4 years into the
                        reign of Humayun. 10 years later Humayun would seek refuge with Shah Tahmasp
                        and it is reported that a number of calligraphers including a later master
                        of ta'liq, Mir Mansur Astarabadi (who wrote in the style of Darvish) and/or
                        his son Mir Qasim (also a master of ta'liq), left to serve Humayun and later
                        Akbar, in India (ref. Qadi Ahmad in Minorsky translation, p.89). These
                        latter two would be candidates for the scribe of the ms, which would also
                        help explain how the manuscript came to be in India. </note>
